The Cu-CDs were used for the detection of molnupiravir, and their fluorescence exhibited a quantitative decrease when the quantity of molnupiravir increased (Fig. S14). The plot of molnupiravir concentration against fluorescence quenching (F0-F) showed a high degree of linearity in the range of 9–120 µM, as indicated by the r2 value of 0.997 (Fig. S14 inset). The limit of quantification (LOQ) and limit of detection (LOD) were determined using the equations 10σ /S and 3.3σ/S, respectively. Here, S represents the slope of the linear calibration curve, while σ represents the standard deviation of the intercept of a regression line. Table 1
                         summarizes the validation parameters for the proposed fluorescent probe in detecting molnupiravir. It includes data on the concentration range (9–120 µM), slope (1.772), intercept (41.224), detection limit (1.978 µM), quantification limit (5.995 µM), and standard deviations for the intercept, slope, and residuals. These parameters confirm the method's robustness, sensitivity, and precision. Common excipients in pharmaceutical capsules were shown to induce negligible effect on molnupiravir quantitation (Fig. 4
                        ). Additionally, the specificity of the fluorescent probe for detecting molnupiravir was evaluated in the presence of antiviral medications such as sofosbuvir and nirmatrelvir. The tolerance limit of these medications was determined as the concentration at which a 2 % relative error occurs [36]. This value was found to be 50 µM for sofosbuvir and 10 µM for nirmatrelvir. The approach was verified in accordance with the guidelines provided by ICH Q2(R1) [37]. The shown recovery rate, as presented in Table S1, provided evidence of the method's accuracy over the range of concentrations investigated. The low inter-day and intra-day % RSD values presented in Table S2 demonstrate the high level of precision of the suggested approach.
